  "prompt": "What is the difference between collateral and mortgage?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between collateral and mortgage:\n\nCollateral:\n1. Broader concept of any asset pledged to secure a loan\n2. Can be various types of assets (car, jewelry, stocks, etc.)\n3. Used across different types of loans\n4. Asset can be seized if loan is not repaid\n5. Not always tied to real estate\n\nMortgage:\n1. Specific type of loan specifically for purchasing real estate\n2. Only involves property/real estate as the secured asset\n3. Typically long-term loan (15-30 years)\n4. Property serves as collateral\n5. Specifically used for buying homes or land\n6. Regulated by specific real estate and banking laws\n\nIn essence, a mortgage is a specific type of loan where real estate serves as collateral, but collateral is a broader term that can apply to many types of loans and assets.",
